1
00:00:08,775 --> 00:00:13,542
<i>The Museum of Contemporary
Art Tokyo, in Koto Ward.</i>

2
00:00:19,152 --> 00:00:22,315
<i>During summer 2007,
an exhibition of work...</i>

3
00:00:22,556 --> 00:00:26,220
<i>...by Studio Ghibli's
"image artisan" took place here.</i>

4
00:00:33,433 --> 00:00:36,027
<i>His works were framed
for the exhibit.</i>

5
00:00:36,470 --> 00:00:40,498
<i>These works were originally
backgrounds and art boards...</i>

6
00:00:40,841 --> 00:00:43,776
<i>...used for scenes in
animated films.</i>

7
00:00:48,215 --> 00:00:51,276
<i>No characters appeared
in these images.</i>

8
00:00:51,952 --> 00:00:56,253
<i>Only the background
for that scene was on display.</i>

9
00:01:14,608 --> 00:01:18,203
<i>But each day the exhibition
was thronged with visitors.</i>

10
00:01:18,445 --> 00:01:22,746
<i>All of them came to see
these "empty" backgrounds.</i>

11
00:01:24,418 --> 00:01:26,750
<i>The exhibit ran for 66 days.</i>

12
00:01:27,788 --> 00:01:33,818
<i>Over 200,000 people
saw Oga's work during that period.</i>

13
00:01:35,062 --> 00:01:37,895
<i>Visitors included people of all ages.</i>

14
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:43,560
<i>The museum staff
were amazed at the crowds.</i>

15
00:01:56,883 --> 00:02:02,788
<i>Most backgrounds are discarded
after production is finished.</i>

16
00:02:03,523 --> 00:02:08,085
<i>But these works found their way to
an art museum, framed for display.</i>

17
00:02:17,204 --> 00:02:20,265
<i>The artist: Kazuo Oga.</i>

18
00:02:20,741 --> 00:02:25,872
<i>Did he ever dream his work
would end up in a museum?</i>

19
00:02:28,081 --> 00:02:31,107
It never occurred to me.

20
00:02:32,219 --> 00:02:36,816
Animation backgrounds and cels
aren't meant to be preserved.

21
00:02:37,624 --> 00:02:41,891
They're usually thrown away
after the film is complete.

22
00:02:44,998 --> 00:02:49,959
<i>Animation background art
is discarded every day.</i>

23
00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:57,034
<i>Background art is the stage
on which the characters interact.</i>

24
00:02:57,978 --> 00:03:03,576
<i>Background art was thought
to have little value in itself.</i>

25
00:03:04,685 --> 00:03:08,087
<i>Among the works
on display here...</i>

26
00:03:08,321 --> 00:03:12,258
<i>...were many that Oga
himself had saved.</i>

27
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:20,465
<i>Background art rarely survives.</i>

28
00:03:21,301 --> 00:03:28,332
<i>But much of this art
captured the hearts of audiences.</i>

29
00:03:32,245 --> 00:03:35,647
<i>Kazuo Oga was art director
for such Ghibli films...</i>

30
00:03:35,882 --> 00:03:38,544
<i>...as "My Neighbor Totoro"
and "Only Yesterday".</i>

31
00:03:39,853 --> 00:03:46,555
<i>Oga's background art evokes
feelings of nostalgia in audiences.</i>

32
00:03:48,962 --> 00:03:54,332
<i>Now his backgrounds, which were
only part of the finished animation...</i>

33
00:03:54,568 --> 00:03:59,631
<i>...are drawing attention
as artworks in themselves.</i>

34
00:04:13,787 --> 00:04:17,655
<i>Oga works quietly
behind the scenes at Studio Ghibli...</i>

35
00:04:18,058 --> 00:04:22,188
<i>...creating backgrounds
that move audiences.</i>

36
00:04:31,705 --> 00:04:35,437
<i>Looking back on Oga's
single-minded dedication to his art...</i>

37
00:04:36,243 --> 00:04:40,908
<i>...we decided to call him
Ghibli's "image artisan".</i>

38
00:04:41,248 --> 00:04:44,240
KAZUO OGA GHIBLl'S IMAGE ARTISAN The
Artist Who Made Totoro's Forest

39
00:04:51,758 --> 00:04:55,626
<i>1972. Kazuo Oga was 20.</i>

40
00:04:55,962 --> 00:05:00,866
<i>One day he saw a job listing
for "people who like to draw".</i>

41
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:03,834
<i>And so he joined
Kobayashi Production.</i>

42
00:05:04,070 --> 00:05:09,031
<i>It was a company specializing
in animation backgrounds.</i>

43
00:05:09,576 --> 00:05:12,568
<i>It was here
that Oga discovered...</i>

44
00:05:12,813 --> 00:05:16,772
<i>...the profession of
background artist.</i>

45
00:05:18,785 --> 00:05:24,656
<i>At that stage, Oga actually
had almost no training in art.</i>

46
00:05:24,658 --> 00:05:25,489
"THE ADVENTURE OF GAMBA"

47
00:05:25,492 --> 00:05:29,861
<i>He learned the techniques
as he went along.</i>

48
00:05:29,863 --> 00:05:31,297
"THE CHAMPION"

49
00:05:31,298 --> 00:05:35,235
It turned out that
the paper for backgrounds...

50
00:05:35,535 --> 00:05:40,701
...was about the size of
the sketch pads I used in school.

51
00:05:41,208 --> 00:05:46,669
I was doing backgrounds
day after day.

52
00:05:47,848 --> 00:05:49,680
I felt pretty lucky.

53
00:05:51,318 --> 00:05:57,485
<i>This is a background from
”The Giatrus, The First Man”.</i>

54
00:05:58,191 --> 00:06:01,752
<i>Art director Shichiro Kobayashi...</i>

55
00:06:01,862 --> 00:06:06,095
<i>...designed daringly abstract,
abbreviated backgrounds for the series.</i>

56
00:06:07,033 --> 00:06:10,970
<i>The style differs completely
from Oga's recent work.</i>

57
00:06:13,139 --> 00:06:17,872
<i>Shichiro Kobayashi is the founder
of Kobayashi Production...</i>

58
00:06:18,111 --> 00:06:19,840
<i>...where Oga started out.</i>

59
00:06:20,413 --> 00:06:23,041
<i>Oga regards Kobayashi
as his mentor.</i>

60
00:06:23,850 --> 00:06:26,717
<i>What was his
first impression of Oga?</i>

61
00:06:27,020 --> 00:06:35,394
SHICHIRO KOBAYASHI
KOBAYASHI PRODUCTION

62
00:06:35,395 --> 00:06:38,956
I suspected he had
potential, that's all.

63
00:06:39,299 --> 00:06:44,829
He had a delicate sensibility.

64
00:06:46,339 --> 00:06:52,142
It was reflected in the way
he handled straight lines.

65
00:06:52,812 --> 00:06:56,749
That stood out
at the time.

66
00:06:57,350 --> 00:07:05,417
Not good for much at first,
but I sensed he had huge potential.

67
00:07:06,359 --> 00:07:09,590
But he was extremely sensitive.

68
00:07:11,932 --> 00:07:16,699
<i>In those days, the company
was very busy with TV animation work.</i>

69
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:20,362
<i>Oga was exposed to
a wide range of techniques.</i>

70
00:07:26,379 --> 00:07:32,842
I had to minimize detail
to complete my work quickly.

71
00:07:33,153 --> 00:07:38,717
I also learned which things
to emphasize, to minimize detail.

72
00:07:38,825 --> 00:07:42,625
The goal is to get the essential
point across effectively.

73
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:46,055
No need to detail
what people will overlook.

74
00:07:46,066 --> 00:07:49,559
"THE CHAMPION"
BACKGROUND ART

75
00:07:49,669 --> 00:07:54,607
I learned a great deal about
how to eliminate unneeded details.

76
00:07:54,874 --> 00:07:58,174
Oga delivered everything
I asked, and more.

77
00:07:58,278 --> 00:08:05,344
The backgrounds he produced
were extremely tidy.

78
00:08:05,852 --> 00:08:10,756
His work had
a consistently abstract touch.

79
00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:17,887
His approach to images
was efficient and skilled.

80
00:08:19,632 --> 00:08:26,038
"HARMAGEDON"
BACKGROUND

81
00:08:26,039 --> 00:08:30,601
<i>Art director Takamura Mukuo
invited him to work on "Harmagedon".</i>

82
00:08:34,547 --> 00:08:38,677
<i>Oga supplied backgrounds
for several key scenes in the film.</i>

83
00:08:39,085 --> 00:08:43,318
<i>He also supplied promotional
artwork for the movie poster.</i>

84
00:08:57,971 --> 00:09:03,933
"HARMAGEDON"
ILLUSTRATION

85
00:09:10,583 --> 00:09:15,714
"DAGGER OF KAMUI"
BACKGROUND

86
00:09:15,889 --> 00:09:20,349
<i>...and further developed his skills
as a background artist.</i>

87
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:25,627
<i>Boundless blue sky,
white snow.</i>

88
00:09:29,936 --> 00:09:33,236
<i>Mighty boulders,
crimson flowers.</i>

89
00:09:36,142 --> 00:09:40,579
<i>These backgrounds reflect
Oga's keen powers of observation.</i>

90
00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:46,117
<i>They are glimpses of
his future direction.</i>

91
00:09:48,488 --> 00:09:50,320
<i>"Barefoot Gen".</i>

92
00:09:51,157 --> 00:09:54,559
<i>Oga has accumulated
a decade of experience.</i>

93
00:09:54,727 --> 00:09:59,460
<i>Now he will serve as art director
on an animated feature.</i>

94
00:10:02,235 --> 00:10:06,365
<i>Oga made numerous trips
to Hiroshima to scout locations...</i>

95
00:10:06,506 --> 00:10:11,945
<i>...and used photographs of prewar
Hiroshima to create his backgrounds.</i>

96
00:10:12,745 --> 00:10:17,979
<i>But later, a friend who knew
prewar Hiroshima saw the film...</i>

97
00:10:18,351 --> 00:10:23,084
<i>...and told Oga that his
backgrounds were not accurate.</i>

98
00:10:25,992 --> 00:10:29,895
I visited Hiroshima and used
photographs of the old buildings...

99
00:10:30,130 --> 00:10:32,098
...as reference
for my backgrounds.

100
00:10:32,198 --> 00:10:36,362
The material I had assembled
turned out to be weak.

101
00:10:37,070 --> 00:10:43,203
Looking back, I realize that
I should have made more effort...

102
00:10:43,543 --> 00:10:49,641
...to consult people who had
clear memories of the prewar city.

103
00:10:51,651 --> 00:10:57,146
<i>"Time Stranger" was an animated version
of Taku Mayumura's SF novel.</i>

104
00:10:58,158 --> 00:11:03,096
<i>It tells the story of
a boy from the future...</i>

105
00:11:03,229 --> 00:11:07,257
<i>...and the teenagers who join
his adventures through time.</i>

106
00:11:09,869 --> 00:11:13,533
<i>The story spans
past, present and future.</i>

107
00:11:16,242 --> 00:11:19,303
<i>The characters experience
World War II...</i>

108
00:11:19,546 --> 00:11:24,677
<i>...the era of the Shogun,
and Japan's ancient civil wars.</i>

109
00:11:33,459 --> 00:11:39,489
<i>Oga's many detailed environments
brought the past to life.</i>

110
00:11:51,277 --> 00:11:55,680
I thought the backgrounds
would go more smoothly...

111
00:11:55,882 --> 00:12:00,342
...if I worked out
the settings thoroughly first.

112
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:04,379
I created a lot of images
that weren't needed.

113
00:12:05,058 --> 00:12:07,322
But I had a lot of fun.

114
00:12:09,362 --> 00:12:14,801
<i>As art director, Oga created
detailed environments...</i>

115
00:12:14,934 --> 00:12:20,338
<i>...based on extensive research
and consultations with experts.</i>

116
00:12:26,479 --> 00:12:30,848
<i>In the course of his work,
he worked with many directors...</i>

117
00:12:30,950 --> 00:12:34,818
<i>...on a diverse range of
background art styles.</i>

118
00:12:35,521 --> 00:12:39,685
<i>During this period, Oga worked on
animated television series...</i>

119
00:12:39,926 --> 00:12:42,224
<i>...and many
short-turnaround features.</i>

120
00:12:42,562 --> 00:12:48,660
"WICKED CITY"
BACKGROUND

121
00:12:52,705 --> 00:12:58,337
<i>All these backgrounds are
from Oga's personal collection.</i>

122
00:12:58,344 --> 00:12:59,038
"HARMAGEDON"
BACKGROUND

123
00:12:59,045 --> 00:13:01,343
<i>Permission to display
these works...</i>

124
00:13:01,581 --> 00:13:05,518
<i>...was readily granted by the
production companies involved.</i>

125
00:13:06,252 --> 00:13:11,588
<i>Their response is e testament
to their respect for Oge.</i>

126
00:13:22,735 --> 00:13:26,831
<i>Oga's first project for
Studio Ghibli...</i>

127
00:13:26,839 --> 00:13:29,604
"MY NEIGHBOR TOTORO" (1988)

128
00:13:29,609 --> 00:13:30,940
<i>...was Hayao Miyazaki's
"My Neighbor Totoro".</i>

129
00:13:36,482 --> 00:13:40,441
<i>The place: the countryside
outside Tokyo, in the late '50s.</i>

130
00:13:41,521 --> 00:13:47,358
<i>An unpaved road
winds through rice paddies.</i>

131
00:13:47,593 --> 00:13:52,429
<i>Scenes like this were once
common just outside the city.</i>

132
00:13:58,604 --> 00:14:02,370
<i>Oga began working with Ghibli
purely by accident.</i>

133
00:14:04,911 --> 00:14:12,819
"TOTORO" IMAGE BOARD
(HAYAO MIYAZAKI)

134
00:14:12,819 --> 00:14:15,311
<i>An art director for "Totoro"
was urgently needed.</i>

135
00:14:16,956 --> 00:14:22,258
<i>One day Oga received a call
from director Hayao Miyazaki.</i>

136
00:14:22,495 --> 00:14:25,362
Miyazaki had
a close relationship...

137
00:14:25,365 --> 00:14:28,733
TOSHIO SUZUKI
PRODUCER

138
00:14:28,735 --> 00:14:30,829
<i>...with an art director
named Nizo Yamamoto.</i>

139
00:14:31,003 --> 00:14:34,997
That's how Miyazaki
heard about Kazuo Oga.

140
00:14:35,208 --> 00:14:37,370
Miyazaki assumed
Oga would be suitable.

141
00:14:37,810 --> 00:14:39,938
Miyazaki has this
interesting trait.

142
00:14:40,313 --> 00:14:43,647
You see,
if Miyazaki trusts you...

143
00:14:43,883 --> 00:14:47,786
...he assumes
he can trust your friend.

144
00:14:47,887 --> 00:14:50,879
TOTORO PRODUCTION TEAM

145
00:14:50,990 --> 00:14:55,223
<i>So Oga joined the
"Totoro" production team.</i>

146
00:14:56,295 --> 00:15:01,825
<i>Oga vividly recalls one of
his early exchanges with Miyazaki.</i>

147
00:15:04,404 --> 00:15:10,776
Once the storyboard was done,
I set to work on the backgrounds.

148
00:15:11,010 --> 00:15:19,350
Miyazaki didn't present me
with any difficult requirements.

149
00:15:19,952 --> 00:15:25,823
So I assembled and checked a set of
backgrounds for him to look at.

150
00:15:26,025 --> 00:15:30,223
I think it was his first look
at the backgrounds.

151
00:15:31,230 --> 00:15:35,997
His reaction was,
"So this is the best you can do?"

152
00:15:36,135 --> 00:15:39,935
He wasn't really upset.

153
00:15:40,139 --> 00:15:44,736
But for me,
it was quite a shock.

154
00:15:48,214 --> 00:15:53,948
<i>Miyazaki asked Oga to pay
close attention to rural landscapes.</i>

155
00:15:54,454 --> 00:15:57,446
<i>To grasses, trees and flowers.</i>

156
00:15:57,457 --> 00:15:58,652
HAYAO MIYAZAKI
SCOUTING LOCATIONS

157
00:15:59,492 --> 00:16:03,861
IMAGE BOARD
(HAYAO MIYAZAKI)

158
00:16:03,863 --> 00:16:07,231
<i>Oga had received
such guidance from a director.</i>

159
00:16:11,537 --> 00:16:17,101
I decided to go back
and redo everything myself.

160
00:16:17,310 --> 00:16:22,976
After that I checked
all the backgrounds very closely.

161
00:16:25,518 --> 00:16:30,456
<i>Oga worked hard to capture
every type of foliage...</i>

162
00:16:30,690 --> 00:16:36,185
<i>...and the changing face of
the landscape throughout the day.</i>

163
00:16:36,696 --> 00:16:41,657
<i>The result was something
rarely seen before in animation.</i>

164
00:16:45,972 --> 00:16:48,373
<i>A clear summer sky.</i>

165
00:16:50,643 --> 00:16:53,669
<i>An acorn, through a hole
in a bucket.</i>

166
00:16:56,716 --> 00:17:01,347
<i>The changing faces of clouds,
moment to moment.</i>

167
00:17:21,741 --> 00:17:27,236
<i>The house where sisters Satsuki
and Mei and their father will live.</i>

168
00:17:33,219 --> 00:17:39,317
<i>The house combines
Japanese and Western elements.</i>

169
00:17:41,694 --> 00:17:46,131
<i>This style of architecture
was actually popular at the time.</i>

170
00:17:52,572 --> 00:17:57,009
BACKGROUND
(WITH KIYOMI OTA)

171
00:18:03,816 --> 00:18:06,308
<i>The earthen-floored kitchen.</i>

172
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:25,765
<i>There is no plumbing.
Water is drawn from a well.</i>

173
00:18:38,284 --> 00:18:43,381
<i>Father's library, in
the Western room of the house.</i>

174
00:18:56,669 --> 00:19:01,129
<i>The wood-fired bath,
heated from below.</i>

175
00:19:08,180 --> 00:19:13,141
<i>Everything is bathed in
warm light from the kitchen.</i>

176
00:19:13,819 --> 00:19:18,052
<i>The scene is empty, but the image
immediately brings to mind...</i>

177
00:19:18,290 --> 00:19:21,954
<i>...z'he father and
his daughters taking a bath.</i>

178
00:19:25,531 --> 00:19:27,693
<i>The veranda, open
to the outdoors.</i>

179
00:19:28,100 --> 00:19:32,162
<i>One can almost feel
the refreshing breeze...</i>

180
00:19:32,405 --> 00:19:34,703
<i>...of a summer afternoon.</i>

181
00:19:35,541 --> 00:19:38,841
<i>Someone from the neighborhood
could drop by anytime.</i>

182
00:19:39,378 --> 00:19:43,781
<i>These unlocked doors are
a link to another time.</i>

183
00:19:46,252 --> 00:19:51,782
<i>Oga based his realistic rendering
on the house of a relative...</i>

184
00:19:52,391 --> 00:19:54,723
<i>...in rural Gunma Prefecture.</i>

185
00:19:55,261 --> 00:20:00,665
<i>Oga thought the house matched
Miyazaki's storyboard concept.</i>

186
00:20:01,033 --> 00:20:04,867
<i>He had his relative send
photos of the house.</i>

187
00:20:05,471 --> 00:20:09,203
<i>The way upstairs
is steep and dark.</i>

188
00:20:09,742 --> 00:20:13,872
<i>It looks like the gateway
to another dimension.</i>

189
00:20:21,854 --> 00:20:27,122
<i>Near the house stands
a huge camphor tree.</i>

190
00:20:36,869 --> 00:20:39,839
<i>It almost seems supernatural.</i>

191
00:20:40,172 --> 00:20:42,766
<i>This is Totoro's home.</i>

192
00:20:59,091 --> 00:21:01,583
<i>And here's the entrance.</i>

193
00:21:13,005 --> 00:21:18,409
<i>Inside, the floor is carpeted
with grass and flowers.</i>

194
00:21:23,916 --> 00:21:25,748
<i>Everything is finely detailed.</i>

195
00:21:26,352 --> 00:21:30,687
<i>Oga made the floor
soft and spongy...</i>

196
00:21:30,823 --> 00:21:35,488
<i>...so Mei would not
hurt herself as she falls in.</i>

197
00:21:54,280 --> 00:21:58,911
<i>Nature's face changes
with each change in the light.</i>

198
00:21:59,451 --> 00:22:02,944
<i>Depending on the weather
and time of day...</i>

199
00:22:03,189 --> 00:22:06,250
<i>...the same place can take on
a completely different appearance.</i>

200
00:22:06,725 --> 00:22:10,855
<i>Oga brilliantly depicts these
changes in mood.</i>

201
00:22:28,147 --> 00:22:30,673
<i>A late afternoon shower.</i>

202
00:22:37,623 --> 00:22:41,389
<i>The bright scenery
is transformed.</i>

203
00:22:50,236 --> 00:22:55,868
<i>When the rain stops,
the once-sunlit landscape...</i>

204
00:22:56,375 --> 00:22:59,436
<i>...becomes a world
of shadows.</i>

205
00:23:20,566 --> 00:23:24,799
<i>This background is for a
memorable scene in "Totoro".</i>

206
00:23:25,037 --> 00:23:30,407
<i>Here, the sisters encounter
Totoro and the Cat Bus.</i>

207
00:23:46,625 --> 00:23:50,755
<i>Later that evening,
the sky is full of stars.</i>

208
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:04,774
<i>You can almost hear
the crickets in the distance.</i>

209
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:13,478
<i>The most' notable
"To taro " backgrounds...</i>

210
00:24:13,719 --> 00:24:17,451
<i>...depict nature's
transformation as night falls.</i>

211
00:24:23,729 --> 00:24:28,098
The aspect of "Totoro"
that impressed me most...

212
00:24:29,101 --> 00:24:33,299
...is the sequence where
Satsuki goes looking for Mei.

213
00:24:33,439 --> 00:24:37,774
The backgrounds convey
the passage of time.

214
00:24:37,876 --> 00:24:42,473
Without Oga, I doubt that
sequence would have worked.

215
00:24:43,215 --> 00:24:45,946
Mei!

216
00:24:48,354 --> 00:24:52,154
<i>Naoya Tanaka is an
art director at Studio Ghibli.</i>

217
00:24:52,291 --> 00:24:57,161
<i>Here is his perspective
on Oga's backgrounds.</i>

218
00:24:58,230 --> 00:25:02,497
It's as if Oga has
a kind of special filter...

219
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:06,836
NAOYA TANAKA

220
00:25:06,839 --> 00:25:08,136
It's not a naturalistic effect.

221
00:25:08,640 --> 00:25:12,599
He extracts the essence of
important elements of the scene.

222
00:25:13,312 --> 00:25:18,216
Then he augments them
to enrich the image.

223
00:25:18,317 --> 00:25:21,548
Oga is very adept at this.

224
00:25:21,787 --> 00:25:27,521
What this does is change
the landscape from something familiar...

225
00:25:27,860 --> 00:25:32,730
...to something that
feels more like déjé vu.

226
00:25:33,399 --> 00:25:36,596
The audience shares the experience
with the character.

227
00:25:44,777 --> 00:25:48,771
<i>A landscape already
stored in the mind.</i>

228
00:25:49,281 --> 00:25:53,013
<i>The audience feels a
mysterious nostalgia.</i>

229
00:25:56,622 --> 00:25:59,023
<i>After "My Neighbor Totoro"...</i>

230
00:25:59,224 --> 00:26:04,162
<i>...Oga becomes an indispensible
part of Studio Ghibli.</i>

231
00:26:15,040 --> 00:26:21,173
<i>So what is animation
background art all about?</i>

232
00:26:29,288 --> 00:26:33,691
<i>In the production process,
characters drawn by the animators...</i>

233
00:26:33,892 --> 00:26:38,329
<i>...are moved frame by frame
against a background.</i>

234
00:26:38,931 --> 00:26:44,233
<i>Before the advent of automated tools,
characters were hand drawn...</i>

235
00:26:44,336 --> 00:26:47,601
<i>...on transparent
acrylic sheets called cels.</i>

236
00:26:48,941 --> 00:26:54,812
PRODUCTION PHOTOGRAPHY

237
00:26:54,813 --> 00:26:59,410
<i>...of cel and background,
photographed with special techniques.</i>

238
00:27:04,189 --> 00:27:07,284
<i>Take this vertical background.</i>

239
00:27:13,198 --> 00:27:16,361
<i>Can you guess
which scene this is from?</i>

240
00:27:19,505 --> 00:27:22,338
This technique is called
"pan with action".

241
00:27:22,808 --> 00:27:25,937
<i>Ashitaka gallops down the cliff
in "Princess Mononoke".</i>

242
00:27:28,413 --> 00:27:32,850
<i>For the completed sequence,
foreground leaves are superimposed...</i>

243
00:27:32,985 --> 00:27:37,354
<i>...and moved a few millimeters
in each frame.</i>

244
00:27:44,696 --> 00:27:48,064
<i>It's over in four seconds.</i>

245
00:27:51,837 --> 00:27:55,637
<i>Sliding overlays is another
specialized technique.</i>

246
00:27:55,807 --> 00:28:00,608
<i>Five separate background cels
with different perspectives...</i>

247
00:28:00,712 --> 00:28:04,239
<i>...are superimposed over
a background base.</i>

248
00:28:04,349 --> 00:28:07,944
<i>The cels are separated
for the exhibit.</i>

249
00:28:08,053 --> 00:28:11,785
<i>But during photography
they are in contact.</i>

250
00:28:12,024 --> 00:28:18,430
<i>Character cels and background overlays
move at different speeds.</i>

251
00:28:18,764 --> 00:28:21,096
<i>This is the completed sequence.</i>

252
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:23,896
Quiet your rage,
I beg you!

253
00:28:25,270 --> 00:28:27,364
<i>A mere three seconds!</i>

254
00:28:27,506 --> 00:28:32,376
<i>A tremendous amount of effort
for only three seconds of action.</i>

255
00:28:37,549 --> 00:28:41,782
<i>A panoramic background
from "Kiki's Delivery Service".</i>

256
00:28:41,987 --> 00:28:45,116
<i>In this "follow and pan" shot,
the characters move...</i>

257
00:28:45,357 --> 00:28:50,557
<i>...across the field of view
and into the distance.</i>

258
00:29:03,709 --> 00:29:08,943
<i>In e live action film, the camera
just' follows the action.</i>

259
00:29:09,081 --> 00:29:14,884
<i>For animation, a correspondingly
long background is necessary.</i>

260
00:29:26,698 --> 00:29:32,228
<i>Some panoramic backgrounds
are quite specialized.</i>

261
00:29:32,671 --> 00:29:36,198
<i>This background
from "Only Yesterday"...</i>

262
00:29:36,441 --> 00:29:39,638
<i>muses e technique
celled "track up and pen”.</i>

263
00:29:43,849 --> 00:29:48,787
<i>As adult Taeko turns,
the camera pans left.</i>

264
00:29:49,755 --> 00:29:53,316
<i>The camera points
to a scene from the past.</i>

265
00:29:56,061 --> 00:30:01,693
<i>The background is drawn
to simulate a wide-angle shot.</i>

266
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:04,833
<i>With some simple
camera work...</i>

267
00:30:04,936 --> 00:30:08,395
<i>...we jump from
present to past.</i>

268
00:30:11,310 --> 00:30:15,645
<i>We can see the distortions
used to achieve this effect...</i>

269
00:30:15,747 --> 00:30:18,409
<i>...when we view
the entire background.</i>

270
00:30:18,517 --> 00:30:20,884
<i>These distortions
are carefully calculated...</i>

271
00:30:21,119 --> 00:30:25,852
<i>...so the result will appear natural
as the camera moves.</i>

272
00:30:28,026 --> 00:30:31,394
Didn't you promise to ask only
at Christmas and birthdays?

273
00:30:32,164 --> 00:30:34,462
You always spoil her, Daddy!

274
00:30:36,168 --> 00:30:41,231
<i>Nowadays, cels are produced
with the help of computers.</i>

275
00:30:41,640 --> 00:30:44,041
<i>Photography is also digital.</i>

276
00:30:44,242 --> 00:30:50,181
<i>Cels and backgrounds
are composited digitally.</i>

277
00:30:54,553 --> 00:30:59,889
<i>But backgrounds are
still produced the same way.</i>

278
00:31:00,158 --> 00:31:05,187
<i>Each one is carefully hand painted,
usually with poster color.</i>

279
00:31:13,171 --> 00:31:23,639
"ONLY YESTERDAY"
BACKGROUND ART DESIGN

280
00:31:23,949 --> 00:31:26,748
<i>...and supervise
the background artists.</i>

281
00:31:28,220 --> 00:31:33,386
<i>He designs the film's
objects and structures...</i>

282
00:31:33,492 --> 00:31:38,555
<i>...to convey the look
of the film to each artist.</i>

283
00:31:41,366 --> 00:31:46,896
<i>He creates art image boards
needed for each background.</i>

284
00:31:48,240 --> 00:31:52,404
<i>He checks each background
produced by the artists...</i>

285
00:31:52,644 --> 00:31:55,238
<i>...and makes corrections
as needed.</i>

286
00:32:01,319 --> 00:32:09,784
STORYBOARD
(HAYAO MIYAZAKI)

287
00:32:09,795 --> 00:32:12,560
<i>He translates that vision
into a more detailed, concrete form...</i>

288
00:32:12,564 --> 00:32:15,761
IMAGE BOARD
(HAYAO MIYAZAKI)

289
00:32:16,768 --> 00:32:20,762
<i>The art director
is truly an artisan.</i>

290
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:25,777
COMPLETED FRAME

291
00:32:34,686 --> 00:32:38,714
<i>After "Totoro", Oga next
served as art director...</i>

292
00:32:38,723 --> 00:32:42,091
"ONLY YESTERDAY" (1991)

293
00:32:42,093 --> 00:32:42,821
<i>...on director Isao Takahata's
"Only Yesterday".</i>

294
00:32:43,662 --> 00:32:50,466
<i>Takahata was extremely impressed
by Oga's backgrounds for "Totoro".</i>

295
00:32:51,736 --> 00:32:55,730
With Japanese artists,
especially background artists...

296
00:32:56,174 --> 00:33:00,509
...the look of their work differs
depending on where they come from.

297
00:33:01,012 --> 00:33:03,538
The quality of
the air is different.

298
00:33:04,015 --> 00:33:08,577
Artists from northern Japan
render air very transparently.

299
00:33:09,020 --> 00:33:13,924
With artists from the south,
the air seems mistier.

300
00:33:14,059 --> 00:33:19,691
This probably comes from
their childhood environment.

301
00:33:19,865 --> 00:33:24,462
Takahata is actually from
Mie Prefecture...

302
00:33:24,636 --> 00:33:29,574
...which is more toward
the south of the country.

303
00:33:29,708 --> 00:33:35,010
But the truth is, he actually
prefers northern Japan.

304
00:33:35,347 --> 00:33:39,477
So he probably likes the
style of northern artists.

305
00:33:39,584 --> 00:33:44,385
When Takahata saw "Totoro"
he was very impressed.

306
00:33:44,623 --> 00:33:48,685
So when he began preparing
for "Only Yesterday"...

307
00:33:48,793 --> 00:33:51,854
...he wanted Oga
as his art director.

308
00:33:53,198 --> 00:33:56,190
<i>"Only Yesterday"
is based on a serial comic.</i>

309
00:33:56,635 --> 00:33:59,798
<i>It tells the story
of little Taeko...</i>

310
00:34:00,038 --> 00:34:04,532
<i>mend her experiences
as a child in the late 7.960s.</i>

311
00:34:04,543 --> 00:34:05,510
TAEKO (AGE 10)

312
00:34:07,012 --> 00:34:12,473
<i>Takahata created a story
about Taeko as an adult...</i>

313
00:34:12,584 --> 00:34:16,248
<i>...combined with
flashbacks from her past.</i>

314
00:34:16,955 --> 00:34:22,018
TAEKO (AGE 27)

315
00:34:22,027 --> 00:34:23,290
<i>...Taeko feels drawn
to rural Japan.</i>

316
00:34:23,395 --> 00:34:28,526
<i>So she goes to visit relatives
in Yamagata Prefecture.</i>

317
00:34:28,867 --> 00:34:33,532
<i>Why did Takahata choose
this location for his story?</i>

318
00:34:35,006 --> 00:34:37,873
Oga is actually
a native of Akita.

319
00:34:38,043 --> 00:34:44,608
So Takahata wanted
to use Akita as the setting.

320
00:34:44,749 --> 00:34:50,586
But to drive the story, we needed
to find a special local product.

321
00:34:50,689 --> 00:34:55,525
Something distinctive
that would work for animation.

322
00:34:56,561 --> 00:35:01,897
We did a lot of research
and discovered Yamagata's safflowers.

323
00:35:02,233 --> 00:35:06,033
Akita didn't have
anything to rival that.

324
00:35:06,204 --> 00:35:09,139
So Takahata set
the story in Yamagata.

325
00:35:10,609 --> 00:35:15,046
<i>"Only Yesterday" features flashbacks
with pale, simple backgrounds...</i>

326
00:35:15,347 --> 00:35:19,147
<i>...and scenes of today's Yamagata
with rich, detailed backgrounds.</i>

327
00:35:19,451 --> 00:35:22,443
<i>The contrast alternates
throughout the film.</i>

328
00:35:25,156 --> 00:35:27,124
<i>Taeko's childhood.</i>

329
00:35:27,325 --> 00:35:32,491
<i>The backgrounds are
somewhat indistinct...</i>

330
00:35:32,631 --> 00:35:35,657
<i>...like nostalgic images
stored deep in the memory.</i>

331
00:35:37,936 --> 00:35:42,965
<i>Takahata wanted to emphasize a
feeling of the distance of memory.</i>

332
00:35:43,308 --> 00:35:47,472
<i>So Oga's backgrounds were
rendered in pale colors.</i>

333
00:36:01,693 --> 00:36:07,462
<i>The simple lines and pale colors
of distant memories.</i>

334
00:36:08,466 --> 00:36:11,492
<i>Unnecessary detail
was to be omitted.</i>

335
00:36:11,703 --> 00:36:15,970
<i>Only the content of memory
would be depicted.</i>

336
00:36:16,708 --> 00:36:20,770
<i>Anything not recalled
clearly would not be depicted.</i>

337
00:36:21,079 --> 00:36:25,983
<i>The flashback scenes were created
according to this artistic vision.</i>

338
00:36:32,891 --> 00:36:35,519
<i>Backgrounds for the film's
present-day scenes...</i>

339
00:36:35,760 --> 00:36:39,526
<i>...are in complete contrast
to the pale colors of memory.</i>

340
00:36:43,535 --> 00:36:48,939
<i>Based on careful research,
these backgrounds are highly detailed.</i>

341
00:36:55,180 --> 00:37:02,644
LOCATION SCOUTING (1990)

342
00:37:02,654 --> 00:37:03,416
<i>...for firsthand experience
in safflower harvesting.</i>

343
00:37:04,889 --> 00:37:09,554
<i>Everyone on the
production team went along.</i>

344
00:37:13,031 --> 00:37:16,899
<i>Visiting the actual scene
of the story is essential.</i>

345
00:37:17,736 --> 00:37:19,966
<i>So much to see
and experience.</i>

346
00:37:20,105 --> 00:37:24,372
<i>The lessons learned have a
major influence on the film.</i>

347
00:37:27,112 --> 00:37:31,049
Photographs alone can't convey
the atmosphere or the scale.

348
00:37:31,783 --> 00:37:37,722
When you actually go, you see
the way mist rises from the valleys.

349
00:37:37,822 --> 00:37:43,556
You have to see the way
the mist looks with your own eyes.

350
00:37:43,695 --> 00:37:46,926
Later you can use
what you've seen...

351
00:37:47,165 --> 00:37:50,829
...as a point of departure
for your creativity.

352
00:37:51,970 --> 00:37:57,340
With photos, you can't judge
how conditions change through time.

353
00:37:59,144 --> 00:38:04,605
<i>The staff boarded the same night train
Taeko uses on her journey.</i>

354
00:38:04,849 --> 00:38:09,616
<i>They left late at night
and arrived early next morning.</i>

355
00:38:10,555 --> 00:38:14,514
<i>This background
approaches photorealism.</i>

356
00:38:14,659 --> 00:38:18,493
<i>It also brings the period
vividly to life.</i>

357
00:38:36,881 --> 00:38:42,115
<i>Background artist Yoji Takeshige
also visited locations in Yamagata.</i>

358
00:38:42,453 --> 00:38:45,582
<i>He speaks about
the role of location visits.</i>

359
00:38:46,624 --> 00:38:52,586
Actually visiting the locale
helps us do a better job...

360
00:38:52,597 --> 00:38:53,723
<i>'(OM TAKESPHGE</i>

361
00:38:53,731 --> 00:38:57,668
...in conveying the
atmosphere to audiences.

362
00:38:57,902 --> 00:39:02,601
Much more so
than with photographs alone.

363
00:39:04,876 --> 00:39:08,244
You have to
see it first hand.

364
00:39:08,479 --> 00:39:12,541
The quiet of an
early morning train platform.

365
00:39:14,018 --> 00:39:19,684
The look of a car driving along
an empty road before dawn.

366
00:39:20,692 --> 00:39:26,529
The silence, the chill
of dew in the morning.

367
00:39:27,966 --> 00:39:30,628
The warmth
of the sun's rays...

368
00:39:30,869 --> 00:39:34,396
...as it rises over
a field of safflowers.

369
00:39:34,572 --> 00:39:39,408
You have to actually
experience these things.

370
00:39:39,544 --> 00:39:41,569
Then what you create...

371
00:39:41,813 --> 00:39:46,375
...will more effectively convey
an impression to the audience.

372
00:39:50,188 --> 00:39:55,718
<i>Like Taeko, the production staff
began picking flowers before dawn.</i>

373
00:39:56,461 --> 00:40:00,523
<i>The thorns of the safflower
are softest in the morning.</i>

374
00:40:00,698 --> 00:40:04,032
<i>That's why safflowers
are harvested early.</i>

375
00:40:04,135 --> 00:40:08,003
<i>The lessons learned
from actual participation...</i>

376
00:40:08,106 --> 00:40:12,065
<i>...make for more
convincing backgrounds.</i>

377
00:40:40,505 --> 00:40:44,772
<i>The sun rises over
a majestic field of safflowers.</i>

378
00:40:46,144 --> 00:40:49,512
<i>You can almost
feel the scene physically.</i>

379
00:41:00,425 --> 00:41:05,295
<i>"Only Yesterday" used a number
of animation techniques...</i>

380
00:41:05,396 --> 00:41:08,263
<i>...that had hardly
been seen before.</i>

381
00:41:08,399 --> 00:41:12,063
<i>For example,
realistic physical movement...</i>

382
00:41:12,170 --> 00:41:16,073
<i>...and natural wrinkles
in the faces of characters.</i>

383
00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:20,175
<i>What impact did this
detailed character animation...</i>

384
00:41:20,411 --> 00:41:22,607
<i>...have on the backgrounds?</i>

385
00:41:23,047 --> 00:41:26,881
I didn't consciously plan to make
the backgrounds very detailed.

386
00:41:27,385 --> 00:41:30,821
But I think I ended up
being swept along...

387
00:41:31,055 --> 00:41:32,580
...by the animation.

388
00:41:40,398 --> 00:41:44,699
<i>Realistic backgrounds
for realistic characters.</i>

389
00:41:45,470 --> 00:41:49,464
<i>The result was minutely
detailed background art.</i>

390
00:41:49,574 --> 00:41:53,306
<i>But Oga learned something
from this experience.</i>

391
00:41:55,246 --> 00:41:59,911
I thought the backgrounds
were simply too detailed.

392
00:42:00,051 --> 00:42:04,648
This was a lesson
I've never forgotten.

393
00:42:04,856 --> 00:42:11,057
I don't think it was necessary
to include that much detail.

394
00:42:11,262 --> 00:42:16,393
The backgrounds
could have been simpler.

395
00:42:18,936 --> 00:42:24,340
<i>"Only Yesterday" featured extremely
detailed backgrounds.</i>

396
00:42:25,276 --> 00:42:28,940
<i>They garnered praise
when the film was released.</i>

397
00:42:29,847 --> 00:42:35,547
<i>But Oga himself came
to a different conclusion.</i>

398
00:42:36,421 --> 00:42:40,824
<i>The lesson he learned was -
do your research thoroughly.</i>

399
00:42:41,359 --> 00:42:45,227
<i>Once you know what
you are doing, you can omit detail.</i>

400
00:42:45,963 --> 00:42:52,096
<i>The result will be environments
that audiences find appealing.</i>

401
00:42:53,304 --> 00:42:58,902
<i>In other words,
less is more.</i>

402
00:43:11,389 --> 00:43:16,452
<i>Before and after "Only Yesterday",
Oga worked on background art...</i>

403
00:43:16,461 --> 00:43:19,897
"KIKl'S DELIVERY SERVICE" (1989)
"PORCO ROSSO" (1992)

404
00:43:24,168 --> 00:43:28,196
<i>With its European settings
of stone and brick...</i>

405
00:43:28,339 --> 00:43:32,936
<i>..."Kiki's Delivery Service" was
completely different from "Totoro".</i>

406
00:43:36,814 --> 00:43:42,184
A former colleague of mine
from Kobayashi Production...

407
00:43:42,286 --> 00:43:45,278
...was the art director
on this film.

408
00:43:46,524 --> 00:43:50,893
I really put
a lot of work into it.

409
00:43:54,432 --> 00:43:57,925
But the chance to participate
in the production...

410
00:43:58,169 --> 00:44:00,797
...was very good
for me too.

411
00:44:02,306 --> 00:44:05,503
<i>Oga's work in
"Kiki's Delivery Service"...</i>

412
00:44:05,810 --> 00:44:09,371
<i>...naturally focused on scenes
filled with flowers and trees.</i>

413
00:44:10,348 --> 00:44:14,945
<i>Miyazaki supplied the concept,
but when Oga was finished...</i>

414
00:44:15,186 --> 00:44:19,919
<i>...Kiki's house was surrounded
with lush greenery.</i>

415
00:44:32,937 --> 00:44:36,931
<i>"Porco Rosso" was also
set in Europe.</i>

416
00:44:37,575 --> 00:44:42,137
<i>Oga says he was not
originally slated to work on this film.</i>

417
00:44:42,547 --> 00:44:45,482
<i>But he decided
to join the project...</i>

418
00:44:45,716 --> 00:44:50,483
<i>...when he heard his friend
Katsu Hisamura would be art director.</i>

419
00:44:51,956 --> 00:44:56,826
<i>Once again, Oga handled many
scenes featuring natural beauty.</i>

420
00:44:59,830 --> 00:45:03,596
<i>To depict the beauty
of the Adriatic...</i>

421
00:45:03,868 --> 00:45:08,430
<i>...Oga imbued sea and sky
with rich, deep color.</i>

422
00:45:13,744 --> 00:45:17,374
<i>Porco Rosso's hideout.</i>

423
00:45:18,149 --> 00:45:23,519
<i>Steep cliff, ocean inlet
and blue sky contrast sharply.</i>

424
00:45:41,439 --> 00:45:44,807
<i>Chanteuse Gina's secret garden.</i>

425
00:45:45,343 --> 00:45:48,938
<i>Beyond the beautiful foliage
spreads the blue Adriatic.</i>

426
00:45:49,146 --> 00:45:52,946
<i>Again, contrast is the key
to this background.</i>

427
00:46:06,530 --> 00:46:09,932
<i>Oga's next project
was "Pom Poko".</i>

