00:46:10,334 --> 00:46:14,237
<i>The setting for director
Isao Takahata's film...</i>

429
00:46:14,238 --> 00:46:16,639
"POM POKO" (1994)

430
00:46:16,641 --> 00:46:19,110
<i>...was the rural Tama Hills
district, near Tokyo.</i>

431
00:46:23,114 --> 00:46:26,982
<i>Drawing on his experience
with "Only Yesterday"...</i>

432
00:46:27,118 --> 00:46:32,249
<i>...Oga decided not to make
the backgrounds too detailed.</i>

433
00:46:42,533 --> 00:46:45,503
I created the backgrounds
for "Pom Poko"...

434
00:46:45,736 --> 00:46:54,008
...based on what I felt was
the right level of detail for the film.

435
00:46:54,912 --> 00:47:00,908
I didn't work on
the basis of what to omit.

436
00:47:01,719 --> 00:47:07,249
I was familiar with the
natural environment of Tama.

437
00:47:07,625 --> 00:47:12,620
I had a sense of
the foliage and the scenery.

438
00:47:12,797 --> 00:47:16,665
I simply created backgrounds
with the level of detail...

439
00:47:16,901 --> 00:47:19,893
...that seemed appropriate
to convey the settings.

440
00:47:21,906 --> 00:47:26,867
<i>In fact, Oga had already moved
to Hachioji City in the Tama area.</i>

441
00:47:27,278 --> 00:47:32,307
<i>This was in 1987,
during production of "Totoro".</i>

442
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:40,886
<i>Oga was excited that
the area where he lived...</i>

443
00:47:40,991 --> 00:47:44,052
<i>...had become the setting
for an animated film.</i>

444
00:47:44,628 --> 00:47:47,120
<i>He drew on
first-hand experience...</i>

445
00:47:47,365 --> 00:47:51,962
<i>...to depict the loss of forests
and mountains to development.</i>

446
00:47:52,470 --> 00:47:55,804
<i>Along the way, he portrayed
the changing seasons...</i>

447
00:47:56,040 --> 00:47:59,408
<i>...with an accuracy
seldom seen in animation.</i>

448
00:48:08,552 --> 00:48:12,648
We wanted to show the lives
of raccoons in detail.

449
00:48:12,957 --> 00:48:19,420
So we had to show how
the raccoons lived in each season.

450
00:48:19,597 --> 00:48:21,292
That was the goal.

451
00:48:21,599 --> 00:48:26,435
Working on the backgrounds
for "Pom Poko" was a lot of fun.

452
00:48:28,139 --> 00:48:30,733
<i>A construction site
on New Year's Day.</i>

453
00:48:30,908 --> 00:48:34,071
<i>A power shovel
stands deserted.</i>

454
00:48:34,178 --> 00:48:39,514
<i>Through the sparkling air,
snowy Mt. Fuji rises in the distance.</i>

455
00:48:40,050 --> 00:48:43,918
<i>This background is like
a modern woodblock print.</i>

456
00:48:46,824 --> 00:48:51,057
<i>Naoya Tanaka recalls an anecdote
behind this snowy scene.</i>

457
00:48:53,264 --> 00:48:58,498
One day during production,
there was a rare, heavy snowfall.

458
00:48:58,936 --> 00:49:03,737
It was still early, but Oga said
he was leaving to scout locations.

459
00:49:04,308 --> 00:49:07,801
He left everyone else
slaving away.

460
00:49:08,078 --> 00:49:13,312
He said it was a great chance
to get a feel for the snow.

461
00:49:13,584 --> 00:49:16,610
To be honest,
I didn't do any research.

462
00:49:16,754 --> 00:49:21,817
I just wanted to play
in the snow, so I left early.

463
00:49:23,060 --> 00:49:28,965
But you know,
it's always good to get out...

464
00:49:29,166 --> 00:49:34,229
...and actually experience
unusual weather conditions.

465
00:49:44,815 --> 00:49:49,719
<i>The changing face of the Tama Hills
throughout the season.</i>

466
00:49:50,154 --> 00:49:53,715
<i>Natural environments
destroyed by development.</i>

467
00:49:54,992 --> 00:50:00,396
<i>Photographs leave a record,
but there is much they cannot capture.</i>

468
00:50:01,465 --> 00:50:04,867
<i>The smell of a breeze.</i>

469
00:50:05,236 --> 00:50:08,797
<i>And the nostalgia
that is "memory".</i>

470
00:50:11,108 --> 00:50:17,707
<i>Oga's work has the power
to awaken those memories within us.</i>

471
00:50:33,130 --> 00:50:38,091
<i>Director Yoshifumi Kondo's
"Whisper of the Heart".</i>

