474
00:50:50,381 --> 00:50:54,113
<i>...was selected to serve
as art director.</i>

475
00:50:55,319 --> 00:51:00,723
<i>The setting was modeled on
Tama City, in the Tokyo suburbs.</i>

476
00:51:01,225 --> 00:51:05,719
<i>The Tama Hills again served
as the backdrop for the story.</i>

477
00:51:09,600 --> 00:51:13,161
<i>A major theme was the urban
environment as nostalgic home town.</i>

478
00:51:14,538 --> 00:51:19,305
<i>The question was whether
Ghibli's artists could breathe life...</i>

479
00:51:19,543 --> 00:51:21,671
<i>...into such an environment.</i>

480
00:51:22,846 --> 00:51:28,478
<i>The art staff made trips together
for detailed location scouting.</i>

481
00:51:32,356 --> 00:51:38,420
<i>"Whisper of the Heart" opens
with this panorama of the city by night.</i>

482
00:51:41,332 --> 00:51:46,771
<i>The film ends with the same view,
this time shrouded in morning mist.</i>

483
00:51:47,271 --> 00:51:52,175
<i>It's hard to tell
this is the same city.</i>

484
00:51:52,543 --> 00:51:57,777
<i>Oga was responsible
for both of these key images.</i>

485
00:51:59,850 --> 00:52:05,345
This is based on the view from
atop the ski jump at Yomiuri Land.

486
00:52:06,490 --> 00:52:14,921
We got permission to enter the park
very early in the morning.

487
00:52:15,966 --> 00:52:19,027
I took the first
morning train out there.

488
00:52:19,203 --> 00:52:24,471
I saw the same sunrise
that was depicted in the story.

489
00:52:27,845 --> 00:52:29,176
<i>"Whisper" sensitively portrayed...</i>

490
00:52:29,413 --> 00:52:32,542
<i>...the emotional lives
of middle school students.</i>

491
00:52:32,950 --> 00:52:38,218
<i>The final scene is
dedicated to their future.</i>

492
00:53:09,653 --> 00:53:11,917
I wanted you to see this.

493
00:53:18,462 --> 00:53:23,195
"Princess Mononoke".

494
00:53:23,200 --> 00:53:26,295
"PRINCESS MONONOKE" (1997)

495
00:53:28,338 --> 00:53:32,206
<i>This enormous background
forms part of the exhibit.</i>

496
00:53:33,677 --> 00:53:36,874
<i>It was used in
the film's opening scene.</i>

497
00:53:37,548 --> 00:53:43,817
<i>This awe-inspiring vista
remains on screen for 26 seconds.</i>

498
00:53:44,421 --> 00:53:48,881
<i>Eight large cels with images
of mountains and clouds...</i>

499
00:53:49,126 --> 00:53:52,096
<i>were photographed
over a large background.</i>

500
00:53:58,569 --> 00:54:05,100
In ancient times the land
lay covered in forest...

501
00:54:05,209 --> 00:54:10,670
...where from ages long past
dwelt the spirits of the gods.

502
00:54:22,192 --> 00:54:27,722
<i>No fewer than five art directors
were assigned to "Mononoke".</i>

503
00:54:28,499 --> 00:54:31,400
<i>This was unheard of.
Why was it necessary?</i>

504
00:54:32,536 --> 00:54:38,270
In "Princess Mononoke",
the hero travels south and west.

505
00:54:38,375 --> 00:54:43,074
Each art director handled
the region he grew up in.

506
00:54:43,881 --> 00:54:46,407
Oga did most of
the northern backgrounds.

507
00:54:47,718 --> 00:54:51,177
<i>A representative scene
from each art director.</i>

508
00:54:51,388 --> 00:54:54,153
- <i>The Em/sh/ Village.</i>
- <i>Ash/take's Journey.</i>

509
00:54:54,258 --> 00:54:58,354
- <i>The Iron Works-</i> - <i>Moro's Lair.</i>
- <i>The Deer God's Forest.</i>

510
00:54:58,462 --> 00:55:04,458
<i>With five art directors,
the settings were extremely varied.</i>

511
00:55:08,172 --> 00:55:10,539
<i>Ashitaka's home,
the "Emishi Village".</i>

512
00:55:10,774 --> 00:55:12,242
<i>This was Oga's responsibility.</i>

513
00:55:17,347 --> 00:55:20,442
<i>Oga's village was based
on the Shirakami highlands...</i>

514
00:55:20,684 --> 00:55:23,779
<i>...and the Shizukuishi
area in northern Japan.</i>

515
00:55:30,027 --> 00:55:35,261
<i>While other staff headed south
to scout forest locations...</i>

516
00:55:35,766 --> 00:55:39,669
<i>...Oga traveled alone
to northern Japan.</i>

517
00:55:41,972 --> 00:55:47,138
<i>He saw mountain highlands
and pristine beech forests</i>

518
00:55:47,411 --> 00:55:51,075
<i>The images he brought back
majestically open the story.</i>

519
00:56:18,308 --> 00:56:24,577
<i>Oga was responsible for
many striking images in "Mononoke".</i>

520
00:56:29,720 --> 00:56:33,588
<i>The awe-inspiring sunrise
over the Deer God's forest.</i>

521
00:56:47,838 --> 00:56:51,866
<i>The giant Deer God
rises into the night sky.</i>

522
00:57:01,652 --> 00:57:05,145
<i>Life returns
to the ravaged forest.</i>

523
00:57:10,861 --> 00:57:16,425
<i>What did Oga have in mind
when he created this image?</i>

524
00:57:18,669 --> 00:57:21,036
When I was scouting locations...

525
00:57:21,271 --> 00:57:25,071
...I saw green shoots coming up
in places where the snow had melted.

526
00:57:25,275 --> 00:57:29,769
I used that image
for this background.

527
00:57:42,526 --> 00:57:45,461
<i>During the creation of
backgrounds like these...</i>

528
00:57:45,696 --> 00:57:49,064
<i>...the director provides feedback
at meeting after meeting.</i>

529
00:57:50,067 --> 00:57:52,764
<i>During production of
"Princess Mononoke"...</i>

530
00:57:53,003 --> 00:57:56,132
<i>...one of these meetings
was preserved on video.</i>

531
00:58:00,143 --> 00:58:02,578
<i>Studio Ghibli, during
production of "Mononoke".</i>

532
00:58:02,779 --> 00:58:06,340
<i>Oga shows director Miyazaki
one of the backgrounds.</i>

533
00:58:07,250 --> 00:58:11,585
<i>Shafts of sunlight illuminate
the lake of the Deer God.</i>

534
00:58:11,822 --> 00:58:14,689
<i>Miyazaki sees room
for improvement.</i>

535
00:58:14,825 --> 00:58:18,193
The light should fall a bit more naturally.

536
00:58:22,666 --> 00:58:24,896
Like it's always that way.

537
00:58:25,369 --> 00:58:28,361
The location was dark, right?

538
00:58:28,605 --> 00:58:31,336
That's how it looked.

539
00:58:31,441 --> 00:58:34,877
If we make it too dark...

540
00:58:34,978 --> 00:58:37,276
...this part will be black.

541
00:58:37,381 --> 00:58:41,648
I think if we just add
a few more rays of light -

542
00:58:41,785 --> 00:58:45,653
This part can be in shade.

543
00:58:45,756 --> 00:58:49,750
But there should be
light falling here and there.

544
00:58:53,930 --> 00:58:58,026
The beams of light should be
distributed across the frame.

545
00:58:59,136 --> 00:59:02,800
I kept thinking the light was too bright...

546
00:59:04,674 --> 00:59:07,473
...but I think this is OK.

547
00:59:08,045 --> 00:59:09,535
I don't think...

548
00:59:09,780 --> 00:59:12,841
...we have to make this ultra-realistic.

549
00:59:13,617 --> 00:59:15,608
How can I say...

550
00:59:15,719 --> 00:59:19,519
...we don't have to make this look real.

551
00:59:19,756 --> 00:59:23,522
I'd like it to have a lot of impact.

552
00:59:23,627 --> 00:59:26,289
Sometimes even real sunlight...

553
00:59:26,396 --> 00:59:28,364
...looks very majestic...

554
00:59:28,465 --> 00:59:32,732
...when it shoots down from the clouds.

555
00:59:34,771 --> 00:59:38,298
We need light beams from
more than one place.

556
00:59:40,410 --> 00:59:45,507
<i>Based on Miyazakﬂs storyboard,
the art director creates an image.</i>

557
00:59:46,049 --> 00:59:50,043
<i>Seeing the image, the director
further develops his vision.</i>

558
00:59:55,325 --> 01:00:00,286
<i>Using all his skill, the artist
realizes that vision in more images.</i>

559
01:00:00,397 --> 01:00:03,856
<i>This is the role
of the image artisan.</i>

560
01:00:08,939 --> 01:00:16,710
"SPIRITED AWAY" (2001) "HOWL'S MOVING
CASTLE" (2004) "TALES FROM EARTHSEA" (2006)

561
01:00:25,689 --> 01:00:28,624
<i>A residential development
cut into a hill.</i>

562
01:00:29,059 --> 01:00:33,155
<i>This is the opening image
from "Spirited Away".</i>

563
01:00:38,301 --> 01:00:42,295
<i>Deep in the forest, a gateway
to a mysterious town.</i>

564
01:00:45,942 --> 01:00:51,108
<i>Oga created this imposing
red gate amid lush foliage.</i>

565
01:01:01,558 --> 01:01:07,258
<i>Chihiro and Haku pass through
this garden of rhododendrons.</i>

566
01:01:10,333 --> 01:01:16,466
<i>Here is Oga's background,
rendered with computer animation.</i>

567
01:01:31,788 --> 01:01:36,089
<i>The magical marshes
from "Howl's Moving Castle".</i>

568
01:01:40,363 --> 01:01:45,699
<i>A vast expanse of meadows
and flowers of dreamlike beauty.</i>

569
01:01:59,182 --> 01:02:03,710
Of course, each flower had to be
added by hand, one by one.

570
01:02:03,954 --> 01:02:08,790
I can't imagine
how many I painted.

571
01:02:10,527 --> 01:02:14,191
<i>How long did it take you?</i>

572
01:02:14,397 --> 01:02:17,264
I don't even remember
how long it took.

573
01:02:22,005 --> 01:02:26,670
<i>The flowers in the foreground
are rendered precisely.</i>

574
01:02:26,876 --> 01:02:29,607
<i>Those in the distance
are less detailed.</i>

575
01:02:30,247 --> 01:02:33,740
<i>This marked contrast between
rough and detailed rendering...</i>

576
01:02:33,984 --> 01:02:36,578
<i>“imparts a feeling
of broad expanse.</i>

577
01:02:50,867 --> 01:02:53,962
<i>Ghib/I artist Na 0 ya Tanaka
sees something special...</i>

578
01:02:54,204 --> 01:02:56,832
<i>...in Oga's depictions
of foreign environments.</i>

579
01:03:00,610 --> 01:03:06,515
I think Oga's European
environments are superb.

580
01:03:06,750 --> 01:03:10,311
When Oga sets out
to depict a scene...

581
01:03:10,553 --> 01:03:15,457
...that he has not seen personally,
he proceeds slowly and carefully.

582
01:03:15,959 --> 01:03:19,088
He examines reference
photographs very closely.

583
01:03:19,596 --> 01:03:22,258
He looks very
carefully at buildings.

584
01:03:22,766 --> 01:03:26,327
He notes differences in
the style of roofs...

585
01:03:26,569 --> 01:03:28,799
...or the way signs look.

586
01:03:29,306 --> 01:03:33,334
Roads and structures are different
from their Japanese counterparts.

587
01:03:33,843 --> 01:03:36,972
He takes all this
carefully into account.

588
01:03:40,417 --> 01:03:42,909
<i>"Tales from Earthsea"
also contains scenes...</i>

589
01:03:43,153 --> 01:03:46,487
<i>...that are completely different
by night and day.</i>

590
01:03:49,893 --> 01:03:53,056
<i>Oga's backgrounds played
a central role...</i>

591
01:03:53,396 --> 01:03:56,422
<i>...in this tale of the struggle
between light and darkness.</i>

592
01:03:58,868 --> 01:04:02,998
<i>0ga's backgrounds also
impart a sense of majesty...</i>

593
01:04:03,239 --> 01:04:07,369
<i>...to the Ghibli stories
in which they appear.</i>

594
01:04:22,926 --> 01:04:26,920
<i>Art directors often look to Oga
to handle certain scenes.</i>

595
01:04:27,030 --> 01:04:30,398
<i>These scenes have
certain special characteristics.</i>

596
01:04:30,800 --> 01:04:33,861
<i>What might those be?</i>

597
01:04:34,938 --> 01:04:38,306
<i>Yoji Takes-hiya was
art' director for "Spirited A way".</i>

598
01:04:38,641 --> 01:04:42,009
<i>He offers some insight
into Oga's special strengths.</i>

599
01:04:42,746 --> 01:04:47,343
There are several types
of backgrounds I'd want Oga to handle.

600
01:04:48,084 --> 01:04:51,918
One would be comparatively
soothing backgrounds.

601
01:04:52,021 --> 01:04:56,754
Refreshing or
heart-warming backgrounds.

602
01:04:56,893 --> 01:05:02,093
When I see this kind of
scene in a storyboard...

603
01:05:02,365 --> 01:05:07,030
...I would want Oga's
backgrounds for that scene.

604
01:05:08,004 --> 01:05:11,463
<i>Over 200,000 people
saw Oga's exhibition.</i>

605
01:05:11,641 --> 01:05:18,047
<i>What is so alluring about animation
backgrounds without characters?</i>

606
01:05:18,748 --> 01:05:20,580
I think animation backgrounds...

607
01:05:20,817 --> 01:05:24,048
...are very accessible
for the average person.

608
01:05:24,621 --> 01:05:28,114
That's because backgrounds
aren't solely the creation...

609
01:05:28,358 --> 01:05:31,350
...of the artist
who created them.

610
01:05:31,561 --> 01:05:34,394
They were created
to fill a need.

611
01:05:35,365 --> 01:05:41,327
Backgrounds don't express
the artist's inner world.

612
01:05:41,738 --> 01:05:44,867
The viewer can
easily relate to them.

613
01:05:44,974 --> 01:05:49,741
That's a major characteristic
of background art.

614
01:05:59,122 --> 01:06:02,558
<i>Animation backgrounds
are only part of what Oga does.</i>

615
01:06:02,659 --> 01:06:06,152
<i>He is active
in many other areas.</i>

616
01:06:09,232 --> 01:06:11,257
<i>Oga supplied lively illustrations...</i>

617
01:06:11,501 --> 01:06:14,562
<i>...for Soseki Yamamoto's story,
"Mouse Tempura".</i>

618
01:06:17,407 --> 01:06:22,402
<i>In the story, a group of men
try to swindle foxes and raccoons...</i>

619
01:06:22,612 --> 01:06:27,140
<i>...by offering them mouse tempura
in exchange for huge fish.</i>

620
01:06:27,283 --> 01:06:31,982
<i>It's a story replete with natural beauty
and humorous characters.</i>

621
01:06:36,125 --> 01:06:39,584
<i>To transmit the experiences
of atom bomb survivors...</i>

622
01:06:40,330 --> 01:06:43,823
<i>...actress Sayuri Yoshinaga produced
a CD titled "Second Movement".</i>

623
01:06:44,033 --> 01:06:48,595
<i>The CD contains poems and recollections
by survivors of the bombing.</i>

624
01:06:57,614 --> 01:07:02,245
"BAREFOOT GEN"
BACKGROUND

625
01:07:02,252 --> 01:07:06,917
<i>...as well as the series
of books based on it.</i>

626
01:07:07,524 --> 01:07:11,290
<i>It was Yoshinaga's strong desire...</i>

627
01:07:11,461 --> 01:07:15,955
<i>...to have Oga
